Biodiversity

Biodiversity

Biodiversity

  • The optimal strategy to maximize biodiversity benefits is to protect 100% of the EEZ.
  • Protecting the optimal 10% of the EEZ would achieve 42 % of biodiversity benefits.
  • Protecting the optimal 30% of the EEZ would achieve 89 % of biodiversity benefits

Carbon

Carbon

Carbon

  • The optimal strategy to maximize carbon benefits is to protect 51% of the EEZ. This would avoid the release of up to 17 million tons of CO2 as a result of bottom trawling.
  • Protecting the optimal 10% of the EEZ would achieve 68 % of carbon benefits.
  • Protecting the optimal 30% of the EEZ would achieve 99 % of carbon benefits

Food

Food

Food

  • The optimal strategy to maximize food provision benefits is to protect 22% of the EEZ. This would yield a net gain in catch of 100,249 tons
  • Protecting the optimal 10% of the EEZ would achieve 95 % of food benefits.
  • Protecting the optimal 30% of the EEZ would achieve 100 % of food benefits

Triple wins

Equal weights

Equal weights

Equal weights

  • The optimal strategy to simultaneously maximize all objectives call for protection of 23 % of the EEZ.
  • This would achieve 56 %, 47 %, 33 %, of the carbon, biodiversity, and food provision benefits, respectively.
